DIV1.P:
One should have expected that the queen would have parted in disgust with the prin∣cess, at this rejection of a match, recom∣mended by Philip, and so convenient to his purposes. But it appears, that the queen was extremely backward in promoting her husband's desire of marrying Elisabeth to the duke of Savoy. On this account, Philip employed Alphonsus, a franciscan frier, his confessor, to confer with her majesty on the subject of this marriage. She told him, that she feared, without consent of parlia∣ment, neither her husband Philip, nor the nation would be benefited by this alliance. She added, that she could not in point of conscience press this match upon her sister;


meaning perhaps that it would be unjust, to force the princess to be married, after her resolute declarations against wedlock; or im∣proper and dishonorable, to match her be∣neath the dignity of a crowned head. The theological reasonings of Alphonsus were too refined for the understanding, or too weak for the conscience, of the queen, who still remained inflexible in her former opinion. Upon this, Philip wrote to her in his usual authoritative style, advising her to examine her own conscience, and to consider whether her opinion was founded in truth or in ob∣stinacy; adding, that if the parliament op∣posed his request, he should lay the blame upon herStrype, Eccl. Mem. iii. 317. seq.. The queen, in her answer, beg∣ged that he would, at least, defer the mat∣ter till he returned into England: and that then he might have a better opportunity of judging, what attention her reasons de∣served. That otherwise, she should live in jealousy of his affections, a state of mind to her worse than death; but which, to her great disquietude, she had already began to feel. She observed, with many expressions of deference to his superior judgment and authority, that, whatever her conscience might have determined, the matter could not be


possibly brought to any speedy conclusion, as the duke would be immediately ordered into the field.

DIV2.P:
I now return to Thomas Pope, the second son of William first earl of Downe, uncle to Thomas above-mentioned the second earl, and ancestor to Francis the present lord Guildford. He was born 1598At Wroxton there is a picture, dated 1606, of William Pope, aged 10, and of his brother Thomas, here mentioned, aged 8.. He was knighted by Charles I. at the royal manor of Woodstock, Aug. 1, 1625MSS. Dugdale, Mus. Ashmol. R. fol. 232.. He married at Wroxton, Apr. 20, 1636, Beata, Daughter of Sir Henry Poole of Saperton in Gloucestershire, baronetRegistr. Wroxton. There is a valuable portrait of this lady at Wroxton, by the second Vansomer.. He appeared in arms for the royal cause. On the death of his nephew Thomas, he became by succession, Decemb. 28, 1660, a baronet, and third earl of Downe. He died Jan. 11, 1667, and was buried at Wroxton: as was his countess Beata, Jul. 18, 1678Registr. Wroxton.. They had three sons, Thomas, Henry, and a second Henry; and five daughters, Elenor, Anne, Beata, Frances, and Finetta. Thomas was born, 1640, and on the death of his father, Jan. 11, 1667, became by succession a baronet, and fourth


and last earl of DowneThere are pictures at Ditchley of the two last earls of Downe.. These dignities he enjoyed but a few months; for he died May 18, 1668Registr. Wroxton., and was buried with his ancestors, in a vault under the chancel at Wroxton. The first Henry was born Apr. 11, 1643, and died an infantIbid.. The second Henry was born Jan. 27, 1645Ibid., and died at Oxford in Trinity college, where he was a student, aged 19, Jun. 20, 1665Ex Tumul. ibid. I find the countess of Downe, his mo∣ther, making a present to the college, "in memoriam filii sui Dni Henrici Pope hujus collegii comm. defuncti." Registr. ibid. in pergamen. ab ann. 1665, fol. 46. Where she is called, by mistake, Elisabetha instead of Beata.. Of the daughters, Ele∣nor died an infant 1637Registr. Wroxton.. Anne was born 1637Ibid., and married sir Edward Boughton, baronet, of Law∣ford in WarwickshireMSS. Pedigr. Rawlins.. Beata, born 1639, was mar∣ried Febr. 15, 1668, to William Soames, esquire, of Thurlowe in SuffolkRegistr. Wroxton.. Frances, born 1647, was married March 5, 1671, to sir Francis North, afterwards lord keeper, and lord North of of GuildfordIbid.; and from this match, grandfather to the present Francis lord North and Guildford. She died Nov. 15, 1678Ex Epitaphio., and was buried at Wrox∣ton;


where is an epitaph on her monument, written by Dr. Henry Paman, public orator of the univer∣sity of Cambridge, who is said to have been well acquainted with her amiable characterNorth's Life of lord keeper North, 4to. p. 84.. The young∣est daughter, Finetta, was married May 4, 1674, to Robert Hyde, esquireRegistr. Wroxton. See Wood, Ath. Oxon. ii. 543.—f. 235., son of Alexander Hyde, bishop of SalisburyWhose elder brother Laurence Hyde, esquire, of Heale near Salisbury, married MARY the daughter of ANTONY WARTON, rector of Bremor in Hamshire, about the reign of Charles the first, and great grandfather to the father of the author of this work. This lady, when a widow, for many days conceal∣ed and accommodated in her house at Heale, aforesaid, king Charles the second after his hazardous flight from the battle of Worcester, in the year 1651, and furnished the means for his escape into France. At the restoration, the king gave her a very valuable picture of himself, when a boy, a half-length, painted by Vandyck, and now in the possession of my brother doctor Warton of Winchester. See Clarendon's HIST. vol. iii. p. 331. edit. fol. 1704.. Thus by the death of male issue, and marriage of the female, this family and name, at least in this branch, became extinct soon after the restoration of Charles the second.
